text: FRANCE LA NOUVELLE CARTE D'IDENTITE Plus petite, inviolable et infalsifiable, la nouvelle << carte d'identité numérique> a été présentée le16 mars 2021. Lancée d'abord dans l'Oise puis dans quelques departements, elle est proposée dans toute la France à partir du 2 août 2021. CEV (cachet électronique visible) Signature électronique sécurisée permettant d'authentifier le document. Puce électronique Validité 10 ans. Image changeante avec date de fin de validité surimprimée. contenant les données biométriques du titulaire (photo, empreintes digitales..) + les données de la carte* 1,68m TARLE/Hg DATEDET 12.02:2020 DELMRANCE Daes d ADRESSE Askest 44 RESIDENCE rue DESIRE DU SAINT PLEIN CLEMENT AIR BAT4 33000 BORDEAUX: FRANCE REPUBLIQUE FRANÇAISE CARTE NATIONALE DIDENTITE /IDENTITY CARD FR, EI NOM/Sumane MARTIN Mays- Ghennmmes Gaëlle, Marie FKA HEUDE ASSANCE/PaSN PARS NOUSAGE Aenatenane OM D'USAGE KPUDOCUNETIO X4RTBPFW4 1102.2030 Sgatase 8,5 cm REPUBLIQUE FRANÇA SE FRAX4RTBPFW4BKKKKKEK<<<KK 07138F300211PFRAKKKK<<<<<6 RTINKGMAELYSKGAELLESMARIESSS tn 3 SEXE/S NATIONALITE Nafenally DATEDE NAISS./Du 13071990 DATEDEXPR (Expiye dale 384213 2adresses peuvent être indiquées. Fond sécurisé se poursuivant sur les bords transparents. Dispositif holographique afin de protéger la photo. Même format qu'une carte bancaire. Eta aussi Aterme, elle permettra de réal des démarches administratives sans avoir besoin de se rendre en mairie ou dans un commissariat par exemple. *nom, prénoms, date et lieu de naissance, sexe, taille, nationalité, adresse, date de délivrance de la carte, date de fin de validité, numéro de la carte, photographie numérisée; empreintes numérisées de Source:ministère VISACTU digitales deux doigts. de l'Intérieur, médias. description: JUSTIFICATIF DE DOMICILE - VOLMUNSTER
text: Liberte Egelit Fraterrité RÉPUBLIQUE FRANÇAISE MINISTERE DE L'INTERIEUR 2D-DOC un nouvel outil pour sécuriser vos justificatifs de domicile 2D-DOC Le ministère de l'Intérieur a développé un nouveau type de code- barres, appelés << 2D-DOC> et apposés sur des justificatifs de domicile. Le nom, le prénom et l'adresse sont alors cryptés dans ce code-barres. Avec le soutien financier de Union européenne, les agents de préfecture ont été équipés pour déchiffrer ces 2D-DOC et ainsi vérifier la cohérence de ce qui est écrit sur le justificatif de domicile en toutes lettres et en code-barres. EDF et Bouygues-Telecom, en attendant d'autres opérateurs, apposent désormais des 2D-DOC sur leurs factures électroniques ou sur les attestations de contrat téléchargeables depuis le compte-client. Ainsi, leurs clients disposent de justificatifs de domicile sécurisés, que les services des préfectures et des mairies ont désormais lobligation d'accepter dans le cadre de VOS demandes : de cartes nationales d'identité de passeports det titres de séjour. description: Infos Françaises on Twitter: "ALERTE - La nouvelle #attestation de sortie  en journée est finalement supprimée. Un simple justificatif de domicile  (document d'identité) est désormais nécessaire pour tout déplacement dans  un rayon
text: PREMIER MINISTRE Liberté Egalité Fraternité Service communcation Hôtel de Matignon, le 20 mars 20 COMMUNIQUE DE PRESSE Les règles relatives aux attestations de deplacement applicables à compter de ce samedi 20 mars sont simplifiées et allégées: 1. Leur présentation sera simplifiée : les attestations mises en ligne sur le site du ministère de 'Intérieur distingueront dorénavant deux situations distinctes: l'attestation applicable le soir et la nuit (entre 19h le soir et 6h du matin) sur tout le territoire national, au titre du couvre-feu; l'attestation applicable en journée (entre 6h du matin et 19h le soir) dans les seuls 16 départements soumis à des mesures renforcées. 2. Pour ces 16 départements en journée, l'obligation de se munir d'une attestation en cas de sortie sera supprimée dans certaines situations : à compter de ce jour pour tout déplacement dans un rayon de 10 kilomètres autour de son domicile entre 6h et 19h, il ne sera plus obligatoire de produire une attestation et donc justifier du motif de son déplacement. En cas de contrôle, il sera demandé de produire un simple justificatif de domicile (ex -S . document d'identité). L'attestat et la justification du motif du déplacement continueront d'être requises pour les déplacements de plus de 10 kilomètres (soit au sein du département, soit pour des déplacements inter-regionaux). Deux nouveaux modèles d'attestation seront mis en ligne sur le site du ministère de l'Intérieur dans les prochaines heures.

description: Lire sa fiche de paie - SUD Éducation 93
text: Sudos Déchiffrer sa fiche de paie Comprendre sa fiche de paie dans Education Nationale est un véritable casse-tète : entre les heures sup' et les primes payées des mois en retard, les codes obscures, il est difficile de vérifier ce qu'on touche, sans oublier que les fiches de paie sont bien souvent distribuées avec plusieurs mois de retard I Le bandeau d'information rassemble toutes les informations permettant de calculer des paies pour La fiche de paie est composée de trois grands ensembles : 1-Le bandeau d'informations Le calendrier l'année 2018 Lundi 29/01 Lundi 26/02 Mercredi 28/03 Jeudi 26/04 Lundi 29/05 Mercredi 27/06 Mercredi 29/08 Mercredi 26/09 Lundi 29/10 Mercredi 28/11 Vemps partiel la rémunération de lagent-e. Plusieurs informations du bandeau sont donc à ventier (CN lec corps (professeur certifié, PE, professeur agrégé, AED...) et le grade le nombre d'enfants à charge : ouvre droit au SFT (Supplement l'échelon : les échelons passés de septembre à décembre Classe Normale, HC Hors Classe...) Familial de traintement), s'applique aux entants jusqu'à l'àge de 20 ans. n'apparaissent souvent qu'en janvier. Vous pouvez consulter votre échelon ainsi que la date de passage à léchelon supérieur sur -prof. calculer votre salaire. L'indice dépend du corps, du grade et de léchelon. lindice ou nombre d'heures : indice de rémunération permet de Vendredi 27/07 la NBI (Nouvelle Bonification iIndiciaire) permet de prendre en compte le Temps Partiel : correspond à la quotite de salaire versé. les points dûs au poste spécifique occupé dans le calcul de l'indice. Ex:o un 80% ou 50%..- Grade PROF. CERTIFE CN 2-L Le détail du salaire Enf,a charge 00 ech. 05 Ind./Nbh. 0466 Thr/NBI On observe ensuite sur la fiche de paie un tableau à cinq colonnes - Codes et Elements indiquent tous les éléments à déduire ou à ajouter au traitement brut à payer : le crédit de l'agent-e, tout ce que lui doit 'employeur, c'est-a-dire le traintement, les à déduire : les cotisations sociales à la charge de lagent-e, elles sont retirées du salaire. brut: pour information : les cotisations patronales versées par lEtat pour lagent-e ( maladie, pour calculer le salaire net. primes et les indemnités. pension civile (retenue PC) = la retraite, CSG, CRDS (Contrbution à la Réduction de la Dette Sociale), Contribution Solidarité (= l'Assurance Chomage), RAFP (= caisse complementaire de retraite)- allocations familiales, retraites...). 3-Le pied de la fiche de paie Ne restez pas isolé-e, syndiquez-vous ! 9-11 rue Genin, 93200 Saint-Denis 01.55.84.41.26 ou 06.88.66.47.23 comthet@ludedicatenar: PatsacwaNV La partie intérieur du bulletin de paie comporte les informations défendez vos droits, concemant ragent-e (son numéro de compte, son numéro de sécurité sociale), la date du virement et les informations détaillées dans le tableau montant pris en compte dans le calcul des cotisations. l'année du 1er janvier au 31 décembre indique le montant qui permettra de calculer l'impôt sur le revenu. Le montant imposable du mois est égal au traitement net augmente de la CSG non déductible, de la CRDS et de la à 5 colonnes. La Base SS (Base Sécurité Sociale) du mois indique le Pour contacter Sud Educ' 93 Le montant imposable du mois et le montant imposable de cotisation pour la mutuelle, votre salaire. le montant net à payer indique la somme qui vous sera versée,

text: La carte postale Lacarte postale est arrivée dans notre boîte aux lettres au milieu des traditionnelles cartes de voeux. Elle n'était pas signée, l'auteur avait voulu rester anonyme. Ily avait l'opéra Garnier d'un côté, et de l'autre, les prénoms des grands-parents de ma mère, de sa tante et son oncle, morts à Auschwitz en 1942. Vingt ans plus tard, j'ai décidé de savoir qui nous avait envoyé cette carte postale, en explorant toutes les hypothèses qui s'ouvraient à moi. le destin romanesque des Rabinovitch, leur fuite de Russie, leur vovage en Lettonie puis en Palestine. Genetic Epidemiology 5:265-275 (1988) Estimating Genetic Parameters of Survival Distributions: A Multifactorial Model Joanne M. Meyer and Lindon J. Eaves Department of Human Genetics, Medical. College of Virginia, Richmond Fora number of genetically influenced illnesses, age of onset is correlated between relatives. In some cases, age of onset also serves as an index of an individual's inheritedi liabiliry 10 an Uiness. Typically, survival models for age of onset distri- outions do not allow for these effects. We have used the gamma distribution as the basis of a model which specifies genetic variability in age of onset. Specifically, we aliow the hazard frequency parameter of the gamma distribution to be a monotonic function of an individual's inherited liability io an illness. Simulations Afijat under various gamma models indicate that age of onset correlations may be strikingly different from correlations in liability. Maximum likelihood estimation procedures were used to obtain parameier estimates from simulated data sets and to determine whether it is possible to discriminate between gamma processes of different order. The results for 1,000 pairs of twins (500 monozygotic and 500 dizygotic) gave parameler estimates that were fairly accurate but that decreased in precision as the order of the gamma process increased. We discuss the effect this may have on inferences made about age of onset. Keywords: age of onset correlations, survival models, gamma distribution INTRODUCTION Genetic analyses of illnesses and behaviors showing a variable age of onset require a knowledge of the cumulative probability of onset by given ages. Some approaches [Weinberg, 1915; Stromgren, 1938; Risch, 1983) derive this probability from prior age of onset distributions. Others [Elston, 1973; Heimbuch et al., 1980; Risch, 1983] estimate parameters of a cumulative age of onset distribution from the data. When the data allow. its use, the Jatter method is more appealing since specific Received for publication January 11, 1988; revision accepted April 22, 1988. Interoffice Memorandum lotacCompany BBgpass Subject: Market Share Study Date: November 8, 1991 To: Ms. R. H. Steele From: Tory Payne Objective: To investigate the relationship between mutagenicity and weight of tobacco burned, tar, cigarette length, and air dilution for RJR products. Summary: Mutagenicity estimates using a nonlinear regression model were obtained on as sample of 24 RJR products. Correlations between mutagenicity (estimated from linear and nonlinear regression models) and weight oftobacco burned, tar, cigarette length and air dilution were determined. Preliminary regression analyses were performed to investigate the relationship of the above-mentioned variables to mutagenicity. Conclusions: Tar and air dilution were the best single predictors of mutagenicity on a revertants/mg tar basis. Tar was the best single predictor for mutagenicity on a revertants/cigarette basis, followed by weight of tobacco burned. Various combinations of weight, length, tar and air dilution predicted mutagenicity better than any variable by itself. However, variables other than these influence mutagenicity since the percent of variability explained ranged from only 48% to 82%.

A-NVASOAUISAD.N Applications of Neutron Activation Analysis to the Study of Age-Related Neurological Diseases W. D. EHMANN, 1* W. R. MARKESBERY,34 E.J. KASARSKIS, D.E. VANCE, S. S. KHARE, J. D. HORD,' AND Departments of Chemistry, Neurology, Pathology, and Sanders Brown Research Center on Aging, Gniversity of Kentucky, Lexington, C.M. THOMPSON' KY4 40506. ABSTRACT Although the etiology and pathogenesis of Alzheimer's disease, Pick's disease, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis are still unknown, it has been suggested that perturbations in element metabolism may, play a role. Even if not causative factors, these imbalances may prove to be markers that could aid in diagnosis. We have employed a se- quential neutron activation analysis (NAA) procedure to determine elemental concentrations in brain, hair, fingernails, blood, and cere- brospinal fluid (CSF) of these patients and age-matched controls. Samples are first rradiated with acceleratorproduced 14-MeV neu- trons for determination of nitrogen and phosphorus, then with reac- tor thermal neutrons for the instrumental determination of 16-18 mi- nor and trace elements, and, finally, reactor-irradiated again, followed by a rapid radiochemical separation procedure (RNAA) to determine four additional elements. Major advantages of NAA are: (1) its simultaneous multielement capability; (2) the relative freedom trom reagent and faboratory contamination; (3) the absence of major matrix effects; and (4) an adequate sensitivity for most elements ofi in- terest. Ranges of concentrations by INAA and RNAA in selected con- trol tissues and interelement correlations in control brain are pre- sented to lustrate results obtained by the procedure. Longitudinal studies of tissues from Alzheimer's disease (AD) and amyotrophiclat- eral sclerosis (ALS) patients are still in progress. Sept1 /995 J.Immunology Identification and Localization of a Developmental Stage- Specific Promoter Activity from the Murine A5 Gene' jun Yang, Michele A. Glozak, and Bonnie B. Blomberg Department of Microbiology and Immunology, University of Miami School of Medicine, Miami, FL 33101 The A5 protein is expressed in pre-B cells in association with VpreB and u-heavy chains, and is critical for diferentiation to the B cell stage. Pre-B cell-specific expression of the A5and VpreB genes is regulated at the level of transcription initiation. In this report, we have identified several DNase -hypersensitive sites 2.5- to 6.0-kb downstream of the A5 gene, which are present in the pre-B cell line 70Z/3, but not in the myeloma cell line J558L. These sites, however, were shown to have no transcriptional enhancer activity as measured by transient trans- fection. Enhancer activity was identified within a 361-bp fragment (-296 to +65, where +1 is the major 5' transcription initiation site) upstream of the mouse A5 gene. This activity is orientation and position independent, and is also tissue and differentiation stage specific (active in pre-B but not B and T cells). Deletion constructs indicate that three adjacent areas (-210to -169, -153 to -64, and -64 to -22) are all necessary for enhancer activity. Pre-B cell-specific promoter activity was shown to reside within the -219 to +109 fragment. Basal promoter activity resides within the -64 to +109 fragment, but is not tissue specific or stage specific. A negative element within the -101 to -64 region is active in all lymphoid cell lines tested and therefore cannot by itself be responsible for the tissue and stage specificity. The data indicate that the elements responsible for the enhancer activity. (-210 to -22) are part of the A5 gene promoter and likely confer the tissue and stage specificity via positive elements within the -210 to -22 region. The. NACS JOINS COALITION AGAINST TOBACCO SALES TO MINORS 84031 At a December national press conference, the National Association of Convenience Stores (NACS) and the nation's largest retailer and wholesaler trade groups launched the most comprehensive effort to date to prevent tobacco sales to minors. The partnering groups, who represent more than 150,000 retailers nationwide, will work together through the Coalition for Responsible Tobacco Retailing (CRTR) with" support from tobacco manufacturers. The primary function of CRTR, a non-profit orga- nization, is to provide training and educa- tional materials to retailers. To cary out this mission, the Coalition has established the Responsible Tobacco Retailer Program - or "We Card" program. - In the next few months, CATR will ship, "We Card" kits to retailers who request them to feature the logo. The kits are troe of charge "With more than 25 million tobacco trans- actions a day in the convenience store industry, it is imperative that our store employees have an array of tools that will assist them in preventing tobacco sales to minors," said Fred Higgins, NACS Chairman of the Board and Chairman and CEO of Minit Mart Foods (Bowling Green, KY). "As a retailer, I can attest to the fact that my store employees are on the front lines in preventing tobacco sales to youth. Regardless of whether a minor is using an altered D or an aduit is purchasing tobacco for a minor, our commitment is to ensure that these illegal sales are not made. This industry-wide program provides retallers with everything they need to prevent tobac- co sales to minors including specific state laws and guidelines wherever a store owner For more information on the program or to request the free store signage and training materials, call NACS fax 1-800-555-4633 a and key in document #226. After a phone conyersation with counsel, we made these points in response to several media calls: 1) Ke've had no chance to study the paper itself. 2) We're in general agreement with portions of the NEJ editorial which accompanied it that said this still docsn't prove ambient smoke harmful. 3) The author, Dr. khite, seems at odds with the Surgeon General who reported last year that ambient smoke doesn't seem harmful. 4) Ke remember Khite as having said in 1975 that no parent should smoke within 50 feet of a Little League ballplayer and as having led two years ago a defeated political Ycargin at TGIC also has had media queries and reports he is pointing out that White is-at odds with the unquestionable respiratory experts who testified in Congress (Jones hcaring) on the subject. Today wc will begin clearing with counsel a letter to editors who published the Khite story, and will use it as evidence of publication accumulates. Kashington Post covered it yesterday,Nek York Times today. Fourth Draft 1/6/92 KMD Merit Ultima Press Release FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE Contact: Karen Daragan Philip Morris U.S.A. (212). 880-4146 PHILIP MORRIS TO INTRODUCE NEW SUPER ULTRA LOW TARNICOTINE CIGARETTE MERIT SETS NEW STANDARD IN SUPER ULTRALIGHT SMOKING New Lowest" Tar/Nicotine MERIT ULTIMA To Be Launched Nationally NEW YORK, January 7, 1992 : Merit Ultima, a new Super Ultra Light addition to the Merit brand family, will be launched nationally on February 18 by Philip Morris U.S.A. The new brand will offer superior taste and smokeability" at the lowest levels of tar and nicotine. New Merit Ultima sets a new standard for the "lowest" segment of the premium market. It offers a flavor alternative to Carlton and Now smokers as well as to smokers who are interested in switching to a - cigarette at the super ultra light level. By using Merit's patented enriched flavor technology and a new dual concentric filter, Merit Ultima offers the great taste heritage of its parent brand and a smooth, easy draw. And, Merit Ultima is the first cork-tipped entry in the category. Merit Ultima kings contain 1 mg. tar and 0.1 mg. of nicotine; and 100's contain 2 mg. tar and 0.2 mg. of nicotine. (more)

Todd, Esq. Tobacco Research Council Glen House, Stag Place London, S.W.1 England Dear Mr. Todd: In recent talks with Dr. Carl G. Baker, Director of the National Cancer Institute, the desirability of forming an international study group concerned with research into tobacco and health problems was discussed. This letter is to invite you on behalf of your organization to participate in this The proceedings will aim at providing the relatively few active investigators in tobacco. and health research programs with an opportunity to discuss freely current and future research programs with the intent of reaching common objectives more quickly. The group will be composed of investigators primarily involved in tobacco and health research oriented towards producing less harmful smoking products. The partici- pants must be both willing and able to share with other investigators what is being learned from their current activities and openly discuss plans for future research in the field. It is thought that by bringing such a group of experts together to review ongoing studies and to plan future investigations jointly less harmful tobacco products will be available sooner and costly research projects will not be duplicated unneces- sarily. The meetings would be held at yearly intervals with the different organizations acting as host. information and study group. -

Small Business SETAL Karen Kerrigan President Small Business Survival Committee Karen Kerrigan is president of the 40,000 member Small Business Survival Committee (SBSC), a nationwide nonprofit, nonpartisan small business advocacy organization representing America's small business and entrepreneurial sector. SBSC works to promote policies and reforms which foster economic growth and entrepreneurship. Ms. Kerrigan is a nationally recognized spokesperson on a wide range of public policy issues, who has testified numerous times on behalf of small business interests before the U.S. Congress. She has appeared on such television programs as CNBC's America's Talking Network, C-SPAN, The Wall Street. Journal Report, European Business News, The Home Business Show, NET's Capitol Watch and writes a twice-monthly syndicated column for the American City Business Journals, an influential network of more than sixty local business journals nationwide. Ms. Kerrigan also serves as president of the Small Business Survival Foundation, a research and education organization that studies the impact of government policy on entrepreneurship and economic growth. She is also a principal in Capitol Hill Research, a political and economic research service. SBSC, which was recognized by Your Company magazine as one oft the most powerful small business lobbying groups in Washington, D.C., has been cited by Investor's Business Daily, The Wall Street Journal, The Washington Times, The Washington Post, The New York Times, National Journal, Business Week, Entrepreneur, Fortune Magazine, Bloomberg Business News, The Boston Herald, The Philadelphia. Inquirer, The Rush Limbaugh Show, The Michael Regan Show and hundreds of local newspapers. 1320 18th Street, N.W., Suite 200 Washington, D.C. 20036 Tel: (202) 785-0238 . FOR RELEASE IN AM'S OF TUESDAY, JAN. 26, 1971 RAMM ASSUMES LEADERSHIP OF COUNCIL FOR TOBACCO RESEARCH New York - H.H. Ramm, a long-time tobacco industry executive, has been elected chairman and president of The Council for Tobacco Research-U.S-A., Inc. He had been act- ing chairman for the last two years. Recently he retired from R.J. Reynolds Industries, Inc., Winston-Salem, N.C. Ramm, a native of Chicago, received his undergraduate education at the University of Minnesota and was graduated from Harvard Law School in 1929. He practiced law in New York City until 1946 and then joined the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Company in Winston-Salem as solicitor and assist- ant to the chairman of the board. He was elected a direc- tor of the company in 1946, became general counsel in 1955, and a vice president in 1970. In 1970, when R.J. Reynolds Industries was formed, he became chairman of the executive committee, senior vice president, general counsel, and a director. He held these positions until his retirement on December 31, 1970. The Council for Tobacco Research had its origin in 1954 when representatives of tobacco manufacturers, growers and: warehousemen organized the Tobacco Industry Research Com- mittee to support research by independent scientists into all aspects of tobacco use and health. The research pro- gram is the responsibility of a Scientific Advisory Board, currently consisting of 10 noted physicians and scientists, which has so far awarded grants to 251 scientists for a total of more than $17,000, 000. 0-

Comments on EPA document EPA/600/6-90/065; Respiratory Health Effects of Passive Smoking: Lung Cancer and Other Disorders (dated May 1992). JUL161992 R.A. PAGES Introduction I have read the draft of this report, and in general I am impressed with the thoroughness with which the authors have addressed the issues raised. Unfortunately, lack of time does not permit me to respond to all of it, but there are some sections of the report where I have put my comments in writing. These comments cover inconsistencies in the report, some possible methodological errors, and a number of My specific comments follow, divided into two sections (the more substative points coming first). Within each section, the order in which the points are presented follows their position in the report, and does not reflect their importance. In a numper of cases, attention to the issues raised would, in my view, improve the quality of the final report. I would particularly draw attention to points 1.9, 1.10 and 1.1. typographical errors. Substantive points 1.1 (page 5-9, lines 13-12 from bottom) . Figure 5-1 is said to show (v]alues of the test statistics (the standardized log odds ratio .) : plotted'. In fact this figure does no such thing; it appears instead to be a plot of the p-values associated with these test statistics. The actual values of the log odds ratios are not indicated in the figure. To show both the log ORs themselves and their associated P-values would need a Ewo-dimensional plot; the associated normal distribution could still be shown along the appropriate 1.2 (page 5-9, second paragraph, and Table 5-8). It is not clear to me why the relative weights have been made to sum to 100 within countries. For countries with only one study (eg Scotland) this means the entry in Table 5-8 is non- informative. Presentation of the absolute weight would be 1.3 (page 5-10, lines 1-5). The first. sentence" here is rather unclear at first. I assume that what is meant is that for any value of x (where x is the list of P-values given in the report: 0.5, 0.4 etc.) the observed number of studies with a P-value less than x is significantly larger than the expected number (which incidentally, is 30x, since 30 is the number of studies involved). I think it would be better to use the word 'studies' than outcomes', and to say 'as large as or larger than : observed'. The six tests carried out here are not independent, and although no claim is made that they are, neither is any warning given that they are not. Finally, I am not convinced by the statement that '(the) conclusion is not attributable to a few extreme outcomes that might be aberrant in some way'. If there were enough of such margin. figures. Similar comments apply to the following three more informative.

PRESS: CLIPPING Publication: L'Avenir du Luxembourg Vers 1'Avenir Issue Date: Readership: 25/06/91 379,500 CONSTRUCTION De l'air dans nos bureaux, par pitié Près de la moitié des personnes travaillant habituellement dans desi immeublesdel bureau en ville (quartiers d'affaires de Bruxel- les, Anvers, Gand, Liège, Hasselt, Charleroi et Namur) se plain- draient d'irritation ou de fatigue dues à la contamination de l'air ambiant, ressort-il d'une enquête menée en mai dernier auprès de 850employés par lel bureau Sobemap, pour compte du consul- tant spécialisé # Healthy Buildings International Inc " (HBI). Pas. moins d'un quart (24 pc). des personnes interrogées prendraient. régulièrement un ou plusieurs jours de congé en raison de maladies ou de malaises liés aux conditions de travail, font apparaitre les résuitats de létude présentée à Bruxelles. 36 % des employés estiment que leur taux de productivité serait: meilleur sils travaillaient dans un environnement plus propre et plus frais. 41 % se: sont plaints à la direction des, conditions de travail: température, manque d'air, bruit, éclai- rage. 54 pc souhaiteraient d'ailleurs pouvoir controlerla tempé- rature du local ou ils travaillent. 52 % estiment que les bureaux manquent. d'air ou sentent le renfermé. Parmi ceux (52-pc) qui mentionnent la présence de fumeurs à proximité de leur poste de. travail, 40 % estiment que l'air est parfois enfumé et 17 % qu'il l'est souvent.

CORESTA 1982 SYMPOSIUM ABSTRACT FORM AUTHOR(s) (indicate presenting author): J. G. Nepomuceno (presenting), A. G. Kallianos, J. E. Wickham, and A. E. Stagg Philip Morris Research Center, P. 0. Box 26583, Richmond, Virginia, 23261 TITLE OF PAPER: REFINEMENTS TO THE FTC PROCEDURE FOR THE QUANTITATIVE AFFILIATION AND ADDRESS: DETERMINATION OF TPM IN CIGARETTE SMOKE STUDY GROUP: ABSTRACT TEXT: A lightweight and disposable filter holder assembly used in the collection of total particulate matter in cigarette smoke was developed as a replacement for the currently used Lucite filter holder. Not only are these new holders lighter in weight (5 grams versus 27 grams for the Lucite holder) but the inconvenient and time-consuming steps of washing these holders in an alcohol bath and drying prior to subsequent use are also eliminated. During the development of these holders, it was noted that certain types of materials, including Lucite, were very sensitive to changes in the moisture content of the environment resulting in highly variable TPM results. These variations become most significant for extremely low yield cigarettes where negative TPM deliveries have been frequently encountered during the analysis. A negative TPM result indicates a loss of weight of the filter assembly during the smoking procedure. These negative numbers have been obtained even when the filter pads were clearly stained by the smoke particulate phase indicating that something was collected during the smoking process. Therefore, the apparently negative TPM deliveries must be a result of an artifact in the smoke particulate matter collection procedure. Experimental data are presented showing that the observed artifact is primarily due to some phenomenon at the surface of the filter holder during, but extraneous to, the particulate occurring matter collection process. This phenomenon is shown to be attributable to the inherent property of certain materials, including Lucite, to easily adsorb In order to minimize the observed bias in the TPM results and thus allow for the collection of more meaningful data, a lightweight and disposable holder made out of polypropylene and polystyrene was developed. In addition to the obvious advantages of being lightweight and disposable, experimental evidence was presented showing that a negative bias which becomes significant at low TPM delivery levels is eliminated through the use of these holders because of their inherent insensitivity to moisture fluctuations in the environment. and desorb moisture from the environment. Newsday (New York, NY) May 1,1998, Friday, ALL EDITIONS VIEWPOINTS; Page A57 BIG TOBACCO CANT CUT TEEN SMOKING By Alan Brody. Alan Brody, a marketing journalist, is the author of' * Cigarette Seduction." THE TOBACCO industry may be guilty of many big lies, but Congress and the public health community may be developing a big lie of their own: that the cigarette companies can undo the phenomenon of teenaged smoking. As Stanton Glantz, author of Cigarette Papers," wrote: The tobacco companics know how to get kids smoking and, But the issue is bigger than tobacco companics. Because the settlement talks with the government are based on the tobacco companies' supposed omnipotence, the likely failure will create a whole new layer of corruption - all the way from illegal sales to fly-by-night tobacco companies to the potential for more damaging products to enter the gap. Adults tend to have a poor memory oft their own youth and why they themselves became smokers. It wasn't because the tobacco companies marketed to them. It was because they marketed to adults and, as teenagers, they desperately A lively grandmother in her 80s confided to me that she started smoking at 10 and quit at 40. That means she began smoking in the 1930s when cigarette ads were still focusing on tobacco leaf quality and Turkish flavor. There were no ads for Leenagers and certainly none for pre-teens. In fact, the country barcly paid. any attention to teens. Conventional wisdom has it that advertising and marketing arc responsible for selling tobacco. It helps. But does it cause smoking? The absence ofa advertising in Finland and, for a while, in Italy showed that cigarettes sell just fine The etiology of smoking runs deeper into the realm of mystery than legislators and public health officials may care to venture. But that is truly where the allure has its origins. Teenagers aren't responding to ads nearly so much as they are Since we as a society have taken no steps to fill a gap in coming-of-age rituals common in other cultures, guess what industry has come to occupy this role? Kids scck a magic path to the "real heart" of adulthood. They will accept danger but they want belonging and a kind of personal guide, the mystical amulet popular in myth. Cigarettes offer this. That When teenagers were invited to tell Congress why they smoke, one: girl said she was ai nonsmoker until she watched a talk show where experts cited depression as a reasons eenagers smoked, "So that's what you do!" said the girl, who Ihave no objection to taxing the tobacco companies or throwing a few perjurers in the hoosegow. But the demand for smoking is a phenomenon that is not covered by the proposed legislation and both the tobacco companics and the public health groups are going to be left with an embarrassing and costly predicament. As the European experience has shown, raising prices works - for a while and then kids have a way of readjusting. A greater fear, as one teenager put it in an interview with an American Cancer Society worker I spoke with: "if you make them so expensive, we'll just go on to In this politicized environment, it is easy to believe that legislation can make magic. Or that the tobacco companies are solely responsible for the rise in smoking. When the Centers for Disease Control announced that smoking had increased 30 percent in six years, they were quite pleased because the implication is that the tobacco companies are to blame. But this was also during the most hostile media period tobacco has ever faced. Newspapers, TV: networks and even magazines that once quivered at the thought of losing cigarette ad dollars now thumb their noses, knowing drug given proper economic motivation, they will know how to stop kids from smoking." wanted to be adults. without ads. responding to their own demands of adjusting to the tribulations of growing up. they are about life and death only adds to their' "spirit power." apparently had been feeling depressed, and she began smoking. other drugs."

Future Imperfect Voices of a Generation Fear for the Status Of American Dream Despite Their Success, Many Feel Their Parents Had MoreCause for Optimism Yet Outsiders Still Want In By CLARE ANSBERRY And THOMAS F. O'BOYLE Staff Reporters af THE WALL; STREET JOURNAL For many Americans, the future seems about as secure as a dandelion puff. An entire generation now reaching middie age is questioning whether they or their children can do better than their parents. Job security went out with three- piece suits, and pundits have coined a new term, dumpies - for downwardly mobile professionals. Today, both mother and father work, not to be rich, but to send kids to college. The complicated family seene looks more like an Andy Warhol canvas than a Norman Rockwell portrait. Statistically, Americans, both rich and poor, are improving their lots. Their buying power has doubled since the 1950s, and their standard of living remains the highest in the world. Others outside the U.S. still believe people can improve their lot in. America: The current wave of immi- grants is the largest since early this cen- Even so, many Americans despair about the future. In part that's because, in relative terms, America's standard of liv- ing isn'tas far ahead a everyone else's as it once was; other countries are catching up. Nor is the U.S. rate of growth as rapid as it once was. And even some affluent Americans have discovered, as their par ents warned, that money doesa't buy hap- piness. The same numbers = one in three Americans - told researchers at the Na- tional Opinion Research Center they were "very happy" in both 1957 and 1990. No amount of money ensures happiness, con- cludes David G. Myers in his book "The Pursuit of Happiness"s rather, happiness Is satisfaction with whatever one has. Warren Bennis, a business professor at the University of Southern California, has another expianation for this widespread and Mahler-like melancholy, Recalling a sunny phrase of the 1930s "the long sum- mer o! the future" - he says today that feeling seems to be missing. "We want a sense 0E arecuon and hope from our leaders. he says - trom U.S. president to corpora esecutive, universuy dean and head of the local charity drive. These themes have been resonating, explicitly and implicitly, in the presiden- tial campaign. Both President Bush and Gov. American dream. But not everyone is grim. Those who have come from the poorest backgrounds or encountered the greatest hardships seem to retain the most hope. Everyone Seems Defeated' When Mark Donnelly came of age in the 1960s, no problem seemed insoluble. In 1962, as a 20-year-old Army private, Mr. Donnelly went to Oxford, Miss., to protect James Meredith, whose enrollment at the University of Mississippi sparked race riots. For a week, Mr. Donnelly stood outside Mr. Meredith's dormitory with a rifle guarding him against attack. One. student spat on him. he recalls. Mr. Donnelly also served in Vietnam. But after his discharge. he marched on Washington to pro- test the war and be came a regional or ganizer for Vietnam Vets Against the War. While attend- ing Columbia Uni- versity, Mr. Don- nelly blocked police from entering a building after stu- dents had seized it. "We were a gen- eration that had hoped the world could be a better Mark Donnelly place," says Mr. Donnelly, now a 50-year- old vice president at Chemical Bank in New York City. "We naively thought that problems were solvabie." his view different. The proportion of households with annual incomes under $15,000 was lower in 1990, after adjustment for inflation, than in 1980 or 1970, but it remained stubbornly close to 25%. "T've become very cynical about the ability of our system to bring about change,". Mr. Donnelly says. "There's a real malaise in America right now. Everyone seems defeated. RESEARCH GRANT FROM THE SWEDISH TOBACCO COMPANY EFFECTS OF TOBACCO SMDKE COMPONENTS ON BIOLOGICAL FUNCTIONS, SIODIDD AT PROJECT TMMME: CELLULAR AND SUB-CEADULAR LEVELS PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR: Erik Arrhenius OTHER GRANTEES: ADDRESS CF PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR: Mljotoxixologiska arbetsgruppen allenerglaroratariet Lilla Frescati 104 05 SIOCKHOIM GRANT: (Number, Date, Amount) 7206 1972-06-21 75.000:- 7206a 1972-12-08 75.000:- SUMMARY OF OBJECTIVE AND METHODOLOGY: Isolated and defined tobacco smoke camponents are to be tested with respect to their possible disruptive effects on the functions of cells and cell-oryanelles, both in purely in vitro systems where the cells and cell-organelles are directly exposed to the substance tested, and in cambined in vivo and in vitro experiments, where functional disruptions are evaluated through camparisons of cells and cell-organelles from exposed and non-exposed animals. It is also planned to carry out a number of studies using a perfusion technique in which the effect of a substance can be studied in a campletely isolated organ provided with an artificial circulation system. The purpose of these experiments is to obtain, by means of greater knowledge of the basic functional disruptions which can occur in cells and cell-organelles in short-term experiments, background material to help facilitate the evaluation of the disruptive effects which can occur in camplete individuals exposed for a considerable length of time to the various substances tested and of the combined effects of several smoke components. The substances to be tested are being selected in collaboration with the chemical research at the Swedish Tobacco Co. (Asst. Professor Curt Enzell).

From: The Tobacco Institute, 1735 K St., N. W., Washington, D. C. 20006 Contact: William Kloepfer, Jr. (Home). 469-8434 (Office) 296-8434 FOR USE AFTER 10 A.M., April 29, 1969 Statement of Milton B. Rosenblatt, M.D., before the House Committee on Interstate and Foreign commerce, April 29, 1969. Dr. Rosenblatt is visiting physician at the Metropolitan and Coler Hospitals and associate attending physician at the Flower Fi Avenue Hospital, all in New York. He is a member of the Council or Undergraduate Medical Education of the American College of Chest Physicians. News Summary "The concept that cigarette smoking is the cause of the increase in lung cancer and emphysema is a colossal blunder, " he says. Dr. Rosenblatt points out lung cancer was well known a century before widespread cigarette smoking. "The only thing new is our ability to diagnose it before autopsy," he says, pointing to only a three percent diagnostic success be: fore autopsy in a German study of 178 cases between 1887 and 1900, and an 81 percent success in a U. S. Study of 363 cases in 1949-1958. "The increase in lung cancer is therefore a direct result of diagnostic progress, he reports. "It has been estimated that a diagnostic error of five percent in males and one percent in female among deaths attributed to pneumonia and other respiratory diseases would have resulted in the same incidence of lung cancer in 1914 as in 1950." X-ray, bronchoscopy, surgery and sputum studies have Dr. Rosenblatt points to the declining rate of increase in lung cancer as being "far more compatible with diagnostic progress than with a true increase." He says that "despite all the claptrap concerning the carcinogenic effects of tar and nicotine there is no valid experimental evidence that tobacco extract or smoke all helped make the difference, he says. condensates can produce cancer of the lung." ###

Rtrntnel Friza Releree June 25, 1992 PHILIP MORRIS STATEMENT CIPOLLONE DECISION REGARDING UNITED STATES SUPREME COURT Yesterday, the United States Supreme Court rendered the long awaited decision on the Cipollone case. In spite of the anti-tobacco interests' efforts to make the decision seem like a defeat for our industry, the fact is that the Court's verdict was a victory for us. There were three basic issues in this case. The first and most important - referred to as the issue of "failure to warn" : revolved around the question of whether cigarette advertising and label warnings, in effect since the 1960s, provided consumers with an adequate warning of the risk factors associated with smoking and health. On this most important issue, the Court ruled in our favor, and exempted tobacco companies from post-1969 legal claims that consumers were not adequately warned. A second important issue was whether plaintiffs can assert claims that normal, mainstream cigarette advertising and promotion somehow undermined the effectiveness of the health warnings. On this issue, the Court also ruled that post-1969 claims are preempted. The third issue - referred to as intentional misrepresentation = related to the question of whether tobacco companies engaged in knowing deception by concealing from consumers information not generally known about the risks of smoking.

PHILIP MORRIS Inc New York, New York CONTACT: Dolly Colby 212-878-2144 COURT RULES KEY FLORIDA MEDICAID AGENCY IS UNCONSTITUTIONAL: SEVERELY NARROWS APPLICATION OF CONTROVERSIAL LAW TALLAHASSEE, Fla., June 28 - A circuit judge in Tallahassee today declared key provisions of the controversial 1994 Amendments to the Medicaid Third-Party Liability Act unconstitutional and held that the state agency charged with administering the state's Medicaid program is unconstitutionaly structured. Charles R. Wall, senior vice president and deputy general counsel for Philip Morris, said the ruling should provide the basis for the dismissal of a claim by the State of Florida. Today's ruling came in a declaratory judgment case filed by the Associated Industries of Florida, Philip Morris Inc. and others. "Because the court ruled that the state agency is unconstitutionaly structured, we believe that the claim based on the state's Third-Party Medicaid Liability Act should now be dismissed, said Wall. That case is pending in circuit court in West Palm Beach. In addition, today's ruling clarified a crucial issue the State of Florida sought to obscure last week in media interviews after the hearing leading to today's ruling. The Court held that the new Medicaid law applies only to allegedly tortious conduct occurring AFTER July 1, 1994, the date the new law In his ruling, Circuit Judge F.E. Steinmeyer said the law "may only be applied prospectively = specifically, to conduct of potential third-party defendants that occurred after the amendments' effective date of July 1, 1994. No party shall be held liable under the amendments for conduct or activities that "This could well be the beginning of the end of this lawsuit by the State of Florida," Wall said. "The State's claims governed by the new Medicaid law are essentially based on allegedly tortious acts occurring before the effective date of this law and therefore cannot be the basis for any finding of liability." The Court also declared unconstitutional the new Medicaid law's provision that allowed the State to join together in a single lawsuit hundreds or became effective. occurred before July 1, 1994," I

Tong Subject: Effect of Tween-80 and Safflower Oil, the Vehicles for Dextromethorphan and Compound 111, on the Citric Acid Aerosol Induced Coughing in the Guinea Pig. The accompanying table presents additional experimental data which may be relevant to my report of June 17, 1971, en- titled Antitussive Activity of Compound 111 in the Conscious Guinea Pig". The coughing experiments were carried out as described in the June 17, 1971 report. Essentially, where the drugs, Compound 111, and dextromethorphan were used before, Data in the attached table indicate that these two drug vehicles did not enhance nor attenuate the cough responses. Thus, as far as the data can indicate, safflower oil did not counteract any possible antitussive effect of Compound 111, nor did Tween-80 provide any additive effect to dextromethorphan. their respective vehicles were used here. INTER-OFFICE CORRESPONDENCE 120 PARK AVENUE, NEW YORK, N.Y.10017 TO: RECORDS COORDINATORSAND INFORMATIONSISTENS DEPTS.: PHILIP MORRIS COMPANIES INC., PHILIP MORRIS INCORPORATED, PHILIP MORRIS INTERNATIONAL and PHILIP MORRIS MANAGEMENT DATE: April 21, 1994 CORPORATION Charles R. Wall FROM: RE: Document Disposal Suspension Notice Litigation has been filed which requires us to retain certain records, many, if not all, of which are already subject to Disposal Suspension under the Philip Morris Records Management Program. Please make sure that disposal of all records, regardless of the media, relating to the manufacturing. testing and composition of tobacco, tobacco products, paper, filter or any other material contained in, relating to or used in the manufacture, testing and composition of tobacco products is suspended. These records should be maintained in the forms and media in which they were originally created. This notice also continues the suspension of the recycling of computer, voicemail, or other electronic backup tapes which may contain records subject to this notice or subject to prior suspension notices, including the Appendix to the Records Management Manual titled Topics Subject to Disposal Suspension. If there is any question about whether a record is subject to this or any other suspension notices, the record should be retained, pending consideration of your legal department. Within the next ten days a comprehensive notice will be sent replacing prior Document Disposal Suspension Notices. That notice will set forth all records which must be retained because of the litigation. The notice will also address ways in which the financial burdens of retaining all forms of electronic and computer records can be alleviated. Cork

PITTSBURGH CHAPTER AMERICAN STATISTICAL ASSOCIATION ANNUAL DINNER MEETING Time and Place: Tuesday, April 15, 1975 Park Schenley  Speaker: Dr. Marvin A. Kastenbaum Director of Statistics The Tobacco Institute Title: Epidemic by the Numbers Dr. Marvin A. Kastenbaum is currently the director of statistics at the Tobacco Institute in Washington, D.C. Prior to assuming this position he was with the department of statistics at Stanford. He has also been on the 1 faculty of the University of Wisconsin and has worked for Oak Ridge National Laboratory, the Institute of Human Biology at the University of Michigan, and thc: Atomic Bomb Casualty Commission. He is a fellow of ASA, the Royal Statistical Society, and American Association for the Advancement of Science. Abstract Overuse of the term "epidemic" by well-meaning public officials and members of the scientific establishment may ultimately yield a diminishing response from the citizenry at whom. it is directed. How often can Epidemic" be proclaimed throughout the land before the inhabitants thereof react as if The Boy were crying, "Wolf, again?

The publication digests scientific papers on subjects related to tobacco use and heaith, from medical and technical journals throughout the world. It is published by the Tobacco Institute. Two of the Swedish investigators, it notes, concluded that cigarette smoking is probably not associated with coronary heart disease, high blood pressure or high blood cholesterol levels. TBHR also reports that lung cancer of all types has been found to be three to four times more common in the Occidental European-American, immigrant population of Israel than in the Oriental (Asian-African) immigrants, even though smoking is about the same in both groups. And. an international survey of eight major metropolitan areas, an English study found, turmed up data called by the author incomprehensible according to current ideas as to how smoking affects lung cancer incidence." Genetics and the Heart The two Swedish studies involved twins. Meyers (213) 641-2051 #S-32 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE James Snapp, insurance broker and former Mayor of El Cajon, today urged his friends and neighbors to support Californians for Common Sense in the organization's fight against the smoking pronibitions proposition, Proposition 5, on the November ballot. "The burden on California taxpayers has reached the limit," Snapp said. "The people, through Proposition 13, said they don't want this kind of spending. "Now comes the smoking prohibitions proposition that will be on our November ballot. It would cost an additional $43 million in local and state tax money to pay for an enormous system of expensive signs (at every entrance to every facility of every state and local governmental entity), law enforcement and court costs. "This additional tax load is not necessary. I am supporting Californians for Common Sense to defeat this needless and costly initiative." Co-chairmen of callrornians for Common Sense, the organization campaigning for defeat of Proposition 5, are Houston I. Flournoy, dean of the University of Southern California Center for Public Affairs, Katherine B. Dunlap, prominent conservationist and civic leader and John F. Henning, executive ecretary-treasurer of the California Labor Federation (AFL-CIO).

MICHAEL A. MILES REMARKS ECONOMIC CLUB OF CHICAGO Tuesday, February 9, 1993 Thank you and thank you ladies and gentlemen. It's a pleasure to be here. When I was invited to speak to you, lasked ira what you might like to hear me talk about. He said that Icould talk about anything I wanted to, as long aslsaid something reallyinteresting. This reminded me of an occasion back in the 1960's, when the comedian Mort Sahl was introduced by a master of ceremonies who said, "Come on out, This kind of introduction is, of course, a comedian's kiss of death, but Sahl, who was both ultra-liberal and irreverently anti-establishment, was up to the occasion. He came out, looked at the MC, looked at the audience, and said Mort, and say something reallyf funny." "John Foster Dulles." This brought down the house. Well, l've been called on to say something really interesting, and while it's probably not house-bringing-down material, I hope some of it will be interesting to you. There are two subjects I'd like to touch on this evening. First, because l've discovered that Philip Morris' size and mix of businesses make it the object of considerable public interest, l'd like to give you a brief overview of the company, and the strategies by which we are managing it. Second, I'd like to take a few minutes to talk about what IV will call "science fiction," the problems that this science fiction creates for businesses in general and our business in particular, and some thoughts about what can be done to solve, or at least lessen, these problems. To begin with, then, let me tell you a little about Philip Morris. In its combined operations, Philip Morris is probably the world's largest consumer packaged goods company. In its component parts, PM is also the worid's largest international cigarette company, the second largest food company Last year, revenues for our woridwide operations totaled a little more than 59 billion dollars, which we expect will again put us in the top ten on Fortune's list of the largest industrial companies when that list is published in April. We have 166,000 employees working in 1,100 facilities in 160 countries around the worid. They produce. literally thousands of different consumer packaged products, selling under hundreds of different brand names. and the third largest beer company. Page 1

B-413 2/29/80 MONTHLY MANAGEMENT STATUS REPORT PROJECT NO.: PROJECT NAME: CO REMOVAL USING INORGANIC SALTS BUDGET: $16,639 PROJECT DESCRIPTION : Principle Project Objectives The principle objective of this study is to evaluate carbon monoxide removal from cigarette smoke using ash or components of ash. The carbon monoxide removal from smoke using ashes, such as coal, paper, wood and tobacco will be optimized. The minerals in the ashes will be determined to elucidate the mechanism responsible for the carbon monoxide removal. The effect of ash addition on cigarette taste and tar and nicotine levels will be evaluated. A procedure for ash addition which is effective, condusive to mass production of cigarettes and acceptable to consumers, will be examined. YEAR 80 MONTH JIL ML Mi € 16 12 8 4 J PROJECT COMPONENTS: Literature Survey Preparation: of Cigarettes co Analysis Ash Analysis Tar, Nicotine Analysis Report 39 Hrs. to Date - 425 Total Hrs. Budgeted = 98 CO removals ranging from 15 to 40 8 have been observed when cigarette ash, coal ash and wood ash were added to cigarette tobacco. Coal, wood, paper. and cigarette ash was analyzed using Xray defraction and electron microprobe. Caco3, a component of the wood and cigarette ash was added to tobacco and some CO removal was observed. Attempts have been made to add ash via the RL but with little success. A study of the effect of moisture on the CO removal of ash has been investigated. M. Skladanowskl PREPARED BY Ag-antyew

AMMONIA DETERMINATION When cigarette smoke is drawn through a Cambridge filter very little ammonia or ammonium salts are detected. Possibly the ammonia in the first puff comes through the filter. After the first puff the increasing deposit of acids on the filter combines with the ammonia and removes it from the gas stream. When no Cambridge filter is used, 95% free ammonia and ammonium salts are: C collected in 80 ml of .018 N H2S04. Since the concentration of ammonia in cigarette smoke is quite low compared to the amount of acetic, formic and other acids present, we do not feel that the 40-70 g./cig. represents free ammonia. Procedure - Two charcoal. filter cigarettes are smoked for each determination. The smoke is dispersed through 80 ml of .018 N H2S04 in a specially designed trap by means of & coarse fritted disc. The solution is added to a 100 ml volumetric flask containing about 1.5 gm. of permutit. The permutit has been screened and washed 3 times with 25 ml. portions of water." The flask is shaken for 15 minutes on a Burrel wrist action shaker. If the desired agitation is not achieved, the flask is shaken by hand. The acid solution is poured off and the permutit is washed 3 times with 25 ml portions of distilled water. Five ml of water and 1 ml of 10% NaoH is added to the permutit. The flask is shaken again for 5 minutes. The addition of 60-70 ml water is followed by 3 ml Nesslers reagent. The flask is filled to the mark with water, inverted many times for mixing, and allowed to stand 30 minutes. 00073440 Blank - The blank is processed in the same manner as the sample; except, of course, the .018 N H.S04 solution contains no dissolved smoke.

One set contained a mixed fruit flavor in the tube walls, and the other set had an apple flavor with high boiling point tobacco flavors in the tube Both sets of samples were attached to 2.5/ 48 C.A. filters diluted by about The concentration of the fruit flavors which were included in the extrusion mixture for each sample were felt to be too high. The fruity notes were described as being overpowering. It was felt by some that the dilution was too great and had reducedi the volume of smoke delivery too much. Five additional sets of samples were smoked. These samples had no filler inside of the tubes. Flavorants were added to the tube wall mixtures prior to extrusion for each set. The reactions to each were as follows: Anise flavor - Strong pack aroma, no detectable sidestream contribution, Fire-cured tobacco flavor - Chocolate-cooked tobacco-like pack aroma, no detectable sidestream contribution, no detectable flavor contribution. Oriental tobacco flayor - Green pack aroma, sharp green sidestream aroma, Black cigar tobacco flavor - No contribution to pack aroma, no detectable sidestream contribution, woody, cellulosic chemical flavor. Burley tobacco flavor - Fermented mowed weeds aroma, tobacco-like sidestream not objectionable. Flavor similar to aroma of rotten weeds. Chris Kounnas pointed out that since these. samples had no filler and produced little smoke, the concentration of flavors delivered was probably too great for the quantity of smoke delivered. It was therefore difficult to evaluate the compatibility of these flavorants with extruded tobacco smoke. VIRGINIA P493" NEWS RELEASE BULLETIN: NEVADA May 15, 1999 Nevada Attorney General Frankie Sue Del Papa issued a letter to about 60. cigarette wholesalers in the state. The letter warned that those wholesalers who do not set up escrow accounts, into which they are required to pay $1.88 per carton for potential judgements stemming from the sale of cigarettes made by uon-signatories or gray-market cigarettes, will face significant fines. The fines are up to three times the amount the wholesalers are required to pay into the escrow accounts. Also, the Attorney General stated that a wholesaler may be banned from selling cigarettes within the state of Nevada if be commits more than one violation. Nevada's "Model Statute. Legislation" became effective on May 24. 1999. In the opinion of Carolina Tobacco Company, trademark owaer and sole importer of "ROGER" brand cigarettes, the Nevada state authorities will have 0o choice but to go after tbe wholesalersyjobbers of gray-market cigarettes. There is no process within the Master Settlement Agreement to cntitle state authorities to seek compensation from the signatories of the Master Settlement Agreement for the sale of cigarettes originally manufactured for export within their state. Carolina Tobacco Company is also of the opinion that Nevada state authorities, as well as other state authorities, will turn to wholesalers/jobbers of cigarettes manufactured by non-signatories. State authorities will be obligated to do so under the terms of the Master Settlement Agreement, if they are unable to obtain compensation from the non-signatory manufacturers themselves. Air Quality in the Home, was produced for the Department of the Environment by the Modical Research Counci's Institute for Environment and Health In Leicester. It looks at five types of pollutants in the home - nitrogen dioxide (NO2), formaldehyde, volatile organic compounds (including benzene and common solvents), house dust mitos and fungi and bacteria. Using data from the Building Research Establishment, aiso released in a report today, it evaluates the potential adverse health effects of these pollutants and puts the findings In a national and international perspectivo. The report recognises that the risks to health from dust mites and nitrogen dioxide are not known, but nonetheless recommends a reduction in oxposure. Whilst the other pollutants studied may be hazardous, the report concludes that there is no evidence that current levels in UK homes pose a risk to health. But, as a general principle, it recommends reducing the HdonN levels of indoor pollutants as a prudent measure. As well as taking an overview of current knowladge, the report dentifies a number of Impor- tant areas for future research. Rathke 416-964-8300 or Laura Gongos 412/471-9600 RATHKE NAMED CEO BURSON-MARSTELLER/CANADA PITTSBURGH OFFICE ANNOUNCES NEW GENERAL MANAGER PITTSBURGH, Nov. 9 - Sheila Wells Rathke, a 17-year veteran of Burson-Marsteller and general manager of the Pittsburgh office for the past seven years, has been named Chief Executive Officer of Burson-Marstellers Canadian operations. As part of Rathke's expanded responsibilities, she will be in charge of developing and servicing business and overseeing all operational aspects of Burson-Marstelers offices in Toronto, Montreal, Ottawa and Vancouver, effective December 1. Laura Gongos, a senior vice president and 14-year veteran of Burson-Marsteller, Pittsburgh, will succeed Rathke as general manager of the Pittsburgh office. "These appointments represent logical transitions for two individuals who have made important contributions to Burson-Marsteler," said Don Cogman, President and Chief Executive Officer, Burson-Marsteller/Americas. 2071277124 Page 1 Note for Padoan, Art *** URGENT *** Sarmento, Roberto Thu, Mar 27, 1997 11:22A AM From: Date: Subject: EEMA To: Padoan, Art Mr. William H. Webb, Chief Operating Officer of Philip Morris Companies Inc., is pleased to announce the appointment of Mr. Jean- Claude Kunz, Vice President Central Europe, to the position of President EEMA Region, effective immediately. In his new: role, Jean- Claude will report to. Mr. Andreas Gembler, President of Philip Morris Jean-Claude began his career with Philip Morris EEMA in 1983 as Business Development Analyst. In 1984, he was promoted to General Manager Eastern Europe and in 1986, he was appointed General Manager for the Levant and parts of the Middle East. In 1990, he was appointed Area Director Bastern Europe and in 1992, Area Director Central Europe. In 1993, he was appointed to his current position of Vice President Central Europe. Jean-Claude has played a key role in the success of BEMA's acquisitions and the development of the emerging markets of Central Europe and the Balkans. With the transfer of the domestic Scandinavian and Finnish markets to Scandinavia / Finland / Baltics /Duty. Free will assume responsibility for Central Europe and is appointed Vice President Switzerland, Central PI Hans Fluri, Vice President Eastern Europe, will assume additional responsibility for the Baltics and is appointed Vice President Eastern International Inc. the EU: PC Georges Diserens, Vice President Switzerland, Europe and Duty Free. Europe and the Baltics. Also reporting to Jean-Claude will be: P Rudi Schweizer, Senior Vice President John Guarino, Director Africa and Levant Jacques Guyot, Vice President Operations Kathleen Linehan, Vice President Corporate Affairs Turhan Talu, Vice President GCC and Turkey Jean-Michel Toinet, Vice President Marketing Please join us in congratulating Jean-Claude and in wishing him every success in his new position as President EEMA Region. At the same time, join us in extending our best wishes to Georges and Hans in their new responsibilitics.

Sample Letter Concerned Citizen April ,1998 The Honorable Office Address Washington, D.C. Dear Senator or Representative United States Senate/or/United States House ofRepresentatives Ia am writing to express my strong opposition to S. 1415, Senator John McCain's tobacco legislation. As a concered citizen, I am offended by many aspects ofthis legislation, including unfair taxes, the creation of a black market and sweeping FDA authority. The McCain bill constitutes modem day Prohibition. The FDA would have discretion under the McCain legislation to ban tobacco products immediately - without any Congressional action. The FDA is an unelected federal agency that should not be given unfettered authority to ban tobacco. Tobacco prohibition would foster an immediate black market and smuggling operations -creating a boon for organized crime. A ban on tobacco products also would be a crippling blow on many communities whose economic stability depends on the tobacco industry. Hundreds of thousands of people have jobs linked to the production, distribution and retailing oftobacco products. High cigarette taxes will cause job losses in every sector of the tobacco industry - from the seedbed to the sales counter. Iam a hard-working taxpayer, and I support legislation that keeps tobacco products out ofthe hands ofminors. However, I strongly oppose any bill that infringes on an adult's right to smoke a legal product. Adults make up 98 percent of all smokers in the United States, and they will bear the burden of the huge tax increases proposed by Senator McCain. encourage you to vote against the McCain bill and any legislation that mirrors the devastating effects ofthe McCain bill. Thank you for your attention to this matter. Respectfully,

June 13, 1988 To: From: A.L. Barnett J. J. Gohn Subject: Video Cassette Promotion Concepts The purpose of this memo is to forward a perspective on the potential tie-in of RJRT and MGM/UA for the purpose of leveraging this union with impactful consumer promotions utilizing pre-recorded video cassettes. In December 1987, focus groups were held in Atlanta to determine how CAMEL and Marlboro smokers would react to promotions which include pre-recorded video cassette films from Paramount Studios. This tie-in with Paramount was identical in concept to the proposed tie-in with The findings of these focus groups, although qualitative, in a single market, from a small sample, etc., illustrated a major lack of interest in buying yideo movies even at a discount price when they can be rented Background MGM/UA. 50 cheaply and so conveniently. Perspective According to 1987 Simmons data, a high percentage of adult smokers own a VCR (38.7), however, only 18% of these VCR owners have ever bought a pre-recorded video cassette. An extremely large majority (97%) rent movies because: Rentals are cheap. Current movies can be rented for $2 or $3 and if they want to retain it, they can just record it on a blank tape. Hit titles are readily available. Most only watch a movie once. Rentals are extremely accessible. Most are rented where cigarettes are not sold but are becoming more available in supermarkets, drug stores and convenience stores.

Introduction: In ny memorandum of 21 May, 1963, "Possible sources of nicotine", I compared the merits of obtaining nicotine from a specialty crop of N. rustica as against producing it from stalks left in the field. The conclusion was that if nicotine were to be produced it should be produced from a crop grown for that purpose. Recently, I came across a publication which explores this very question in some On the basis of the results presented it becomes possible to formulate. a detail and conf irms our preliminary conclusions. pilot program which is presented below for your consideration. 2. Summary of Prior Field Trials: The exper iences of the U.S.D.A., covering the period 1929-1938, in growing tobacco as a source of nicotine are collected in U.S.D.A. Technical Bulletin No. 820, June 1942. This publication is available in the A.T.C. library under catalog No. T-7445 hence only the pertinent highlights will be reiterated here. a. Available nicotine from commercial types of tobacco, if entire leaf crop b. N. rustica, var. Brasilia, consistently yiclded 150 lbs. or more per acre when grown on fertile, moist soils. The whole plant of N. rustica can be used for extraction whereas stalks of commercial tobaccos, owing to their high degree of lignification, are not eesily disrupted for extraction. C. The comparative tests were conducted in field plots widely scattered around the country, including plots in Virginia (Bowling Green and Arlington), Pennsylvania, Wisconein, Missouri, Oregon, California, North Carolina, Tennessee and a few others. As a result a wide variety of soils and climatic conditions d. When grown on typical soils of the dark-fired area, or in extreme southern regions, N. rustica did not outyield standard commercial varieties. However, when grown on moist land approaching well-drained river bottom lands, it yielded in excess of 100 lbs.of nicotine per acre even in these regions. were used for extraction, would be between 20-40 lbs. per acre. were compared. Does Bermuda 100 fit the latter category? 3. Suggested Course of Action: If the project is to be pursucd further, the following steps are recomended: a. July 9, 1998 ABSTRACT A series of four independent, two-stage SENCAR: mouse skin painting bioassays were conducted with cigarette smoke condensates to examine the tumor promotion potential of 150 flavoring ingredients commonly used in the manufacture of American-style blended cigarettes. Groups consisting of 30 to 50 female SENCAR mice each were used; animals were treated once dermally with 50 g ot7,12-dimethylbenz@)-anthracene as a tumor initiator. One week later, and thrice weekly for the next 26 weeks, mice. received either 10 or 20 mg of smoke condensate from Test cigarettes containing mixtures of cigarette tobacco flavoring ingredients. For comparison, separate groups of mice were treated concurrently with smoke condensates prepared from Reference cigarettes having similar construction and tobacco blend, but without added flavoring ingredients. Negative and positive controls were treated with either acetone or 12-0- tradecanoyl-phorbol-13-acetate as promoters, respectively. Virtually all mice treated with the positive control material developed tumors and died prior to the scheduled study termination points. Background tumor formation and mortality were very low in all negative control groups. Survival rates and terminal body weights of mice treated with condensate samples from Test cigarettes were not significantly. different from mice treated with condensates from Reference cigarettes. Similarly, the incidence of animals with actual tumors (grossly observable tumors at study termination), incidence of animals with cumulative fumor (maintained count ofall tumors present for three consecutive weeks during E latency of cumulative tumors and tumor multiplicity in mice exposed to condensates from Test cigarettes with flavoring ingredients were not different from, values obtained Mn mice treated with Reference cigarette condensate. The results indicate that the addition of the flavoring ingredients to cigarette tobacco had no discemible effect on common indices of tumorigenic response normally associated with mouse skin painting bioassays using non-flavored cigarette smoke condensates. any les A yhe A 2

Tadayoshi Higashiyama. Kenji Shimizu', Endocrine Biochemistry Depanment, Medical Foundauon of Buffalo Rescarch lnsutute. Buffalo. N.Y.. USA Placental Proteins : Nonsmoking Mothers Nobutaka oshida' COPY FILE The presence of different monooxygenase activities has been docu- mented in human placental microsomes. The predominating cyrochrome P- 450, that of androgen aromatase, catalyzes the biosynthesis of estrogens [1). Aromatase P-450 has been the object of numerous studies to determine its mechanism of action and to purify it [2, 3). Gough et al. 14) reported the presence of another enzyme system which catalyzes the hydroxylation of xenobiotic substances. It has aiso been reported that a placental cytochrome P-450 is responsible for the hydroxylation of benzola)pyrene via aryl hydro- carbon hydroxylase [5-7). The low content of the responding cytochrome P- 450 in human placenta and instability during purification have made it difficult to isolate any other active P-450 enzyme. As a side benefit gained from our procedure to purify and characterize catalytically active aromatase P-450 [3), we found a fraction from the mmunoafinity chromatography which showed a high level of xenobiotic activity with little contaminating aromatase activity. Through the uscofconventional purification procedures, we obtained a xenobiotically active P-450 with no aromatase activity. Previous studies on aryl hydrocarbon hydroxylase activity have demon- strated higher levels of this activity in smokers but not in nonsmokers (8,9). SALONEN,t PIRJO POYHIA, KAJ KOSKELA,T AND "National Public Health Institute, Department of Epidemiology, Mannerheimintie 166, 00280 Helsinki 28, Finland, tUniversity of Kuopio, Research Institute of Public Health, PL 40, 70101 Kuopio 10, Finland. and Harvard School of Public Health, Department A school and community based intervention to influence health behavior and cardiovas- cular disease (CVD) risk factors in 13- to 5-year-old children was carried out in North Karelia, Finland. The intervention was carried out on two leveis: (a) an intensive interven- tion (ID) in two schools and (b) a county-wide intervention (CI) in the rest of North Karelia. For the evaluation three matched pairs of schoois were chosen: the two schools of the II, two schools to represent the CI and two schools from a reference. county (R). 851 children, their parents, and their teachers were studied at the outset in 1978 and after the intervention in 1980. During the program the proportion of boys reporting to smoke at least I-2 times per month increased 12.6%0 in II, 8.2% in CI and 29.7% in the R schools (P < 0.001 between II and R) and in giris 9.0%6, 18.056 and 20.0%, respectively, (P < 0.05 between II and R). The mean serum total cholesterol was 5.1 mmolliter in 1978 and it decreased among boys 0.5 mmolliter: in all three school groups. Among girls. the decrease was 0.43 mmolliter (II), 0.35 mmoliter (CI), and 0.21 mmol/liter (R)P < 0.01 between, II and R). The mean: amount offat from milk and butter changed among boys -8 g (II), 0g (CI), and +3 g (R) and among girls -168, -2g, and -5g,respectivelyl (both P <0.01 between, II and R). The intervention! had no effect on blood pressure although there was some reported. reduction in the salt consump- tion in the intervention schools. A relative decrease according to the intervention level was ob- served: among North Karelian chidren in occurrence of psychosomatic: symptoms. The effects were not related to increases in bealth knowiedge or changes in attitudes and did not lead, on Cardiovascular diseases (CVD) are the major, singular public health problem in most of the industrial worid, but especially in Finland (6, 11). A number of pro- spective studies have indicated that possibilities for CVD prevention lie in reduc- tion of well established risk factors: smoking, elevated serum cholesterol, and hypertension (6, 18, 22). Several preventive trials among adults are under way to test the hypothesis that risk factor reduction in the population will lead to reduced mortality and morbidity from CVD (17,25, 29). AVENUE, NEWYORK, NY 10017-5592 DATE: May 13, 1991 TO: FROM: Distribution Marketing Information & Analysis/Ellen Fitzgerald SUBJECT: EULLMARGINICMPBITIVE COUPONACTMITY Attached is the latest competitive supermarket coupon information (through March 24, 1991) as reported by various data sources. Note: Media-delivered couponing information as reported by the Advertising Checking Bureau is currently available through February. SUMMARY RJR reduced the overall level of coupon support behind their Full Margin brands. This shift was driven by reductions in on-carton/in-store couponing. Philip Morris' Full Margin couponing increased versus a year-ago due to the various Fourth Quarter 1990 Direct Mail programs for Marlboro, Merit and Benson & Hedges. Lorillard significantly increased coupon. support behind Newport, Kent and True. importantly, this higher value coupon activity has had a positive impact on the brands' share pertormance in the supermarket trade class (as reported by the InfoScan Rapid Fact data base). In addition, Lorillard is using a new coupon delivery system: Register Receipt Coupons which delivers $5.00 coupons for Newport to American and Brown & Williamson are focusing their couponing efforts behind their Price Value/Sub-Generic brands and have consequently reduced support for the consumers at retail. manutacturers Full Margin businesses. HIGHLIGHTS Supermarket Full Margin couponing trends continue to be driven primarily by R.J. Reynolds (40% of volume sold on coupon) and Lorillard's recent emphasis behind their Full Margin brands (37% of volume) for the four-week period ending March 24th. However, note that RJR's Full Margin couponing has lost momentum during First Quarter 1991. Full Margin's percent volume sold on coupon for the manutacturer is down from a high of 51% at the end of 1990 to its current level of 40%. Price Value couponing for R.J. Reynolds remained stable at around 62% Couponing for RJR's Full Margin brands declined primarily as a result of decreasing in-store/on-carton coupon activity. For the most current four-week period, the percent of stores with on-carton couponing for Winston decreased -24 points to 14% versus the prior period; Salem, -27 points to 16%; Camel, -27 points to 17%; and Vantage, With the exception of Camel, however, Full Margin coupon activity (supported by media-delivered programs) for Winston (42% of volume sold on coupon), Salem (45%) and Vantage (57%) remained high relative to the industry average. Camel experienced a significant decline in volume sold on coupon (-16 points to only 19%) due in part to reductions after the introductory support behind Ultra Lights. Additionally, it is likely that RJR is reducing the levei of in-store/on-carton couponing behind the brand to refocus support to Camel on pack sales in Convenience Outlets. during First Quarter 1991. -24 points to 18%.
